{
  "texts": [
    "The Low-Rank Adaptation (LoRA) method enables the training of certain dense layers in a neural network separately from the model's trained weights.",
    "This is achieved by optimizing the rank-decomposition matrices of the dense layers during the adaptation process.",
    "LoRA makes training more efficient and lowers the hardware barrier to entry by up to 3 times when using adaptive optimizers since we do not need to calculate the gradients or maintain the optimizer states for most parameters.",
    "Instead, we only optimize the injected, much smaller low-rank matrices.",
    "LoRA's linear design allows the merging of the trainable matrices with the frozen weights when deployed, introducing no inference latency compared to a fully finetuned model by construction."
  ]
}